When a server returns a Content-Type HTTP header without a value ("Content-Type:\r\n") an exception is thrown parsing the value when creating a Mule Message. While this is not probably a valid header when trying the same request with Firefox or Chrome the header is ignored so it would be reasonable to validate the header value before trying to use it and ignore if not valid.

This also happens when receiving a content type ended in a semicolon:
Content-Type: image/tiff;

